@Manatee, thank you for owning up. Please note that I never said you should not voice your concerns. So I would not expect you to apologize for pointing out something respectfully that you faced or experienced. There is no need to sugarcoat either. In fact, I would appreciate it if you could be honest and convey it strongly, but with respect. No more and no less. Because it's the only way we can do better.
I did work closely with the previous director. I did not work closely with the current director, at least technically. I simply tried to show how some of the points you used to assert some of your claims are not very logical and could be misleading. As they might not be telling the entire picture, this is at best an oversimplification with presumptions. I will pass on your message when I talk with him.
@Moose, read again what I wrote. I quoted them clearly. They were directed both towards the director and towards Kamrul. @Manatee was kind enough to acknowledge, which I appreciate. I do not want to silence you guys. I would not prefer to be working in an environment where people can't talk openly. But that doesn't mean I won't speak out against disrespect or distortions. It doesn't matter to whom it is directed; whether it's the director or the office staff. They are all our peers, and we should maintain professionalism and decency.
@Camel, don't mean any disrespect but laughed hard at this - "As a non engineer myself I can very clearly see who has contributed where". Make sure to get your opinion peer-reviewed by a non-engineer üôÇ. I worked closely with the previous director, and I hold him in high regard both technically and as a person. You could very well be right in your opinions about the current director (won't comment as I don't have enough data to form an opinion), but the metrics you are using to come to your conclusions are laughably absurd and illogical. I just double-checked it again, and I will stand by what I said earlier. The goal of a manager/director is to act as a catalyst and lead the team. It is both sad and funny to see people judging them by GitHub commits.
@Alligator, it's not a good metric to judge someone. Not in a company like this, at least. If loitering in the smoking room and having coffee gives you the impression that the engineering director is not competent or not doing his job well, then I dread to imagine what you would think of us if you joined us 10 years ago. The office used to be more fun than home for many of us. It was also a great place to learn from our peers. We worked in unconventional ways. There were days when many of us didn't work much, but there were also many days when we crushed it. We had that flexibility, compassion, and culture, which is what made us great in the long run. Isn't it ironic how that greatness and brand itself appealed to many of you when you joined here? So why can't you see that in a way, maybe you are trying to take away all those unconventional things that made us great and turn us into another typical company without actively realizing it?
Why does it matter what someone is doing at the office? As long as they are handling their responsibilities well, and provided you are not being adversely impacted by them? If their manager and teammates are happy, why should others complain? There is no need to micromanage or monitor their behavior. And if they are not handling their responsibilities or you are being impacted, please communicate with them first. If it doesn't get resolved, talk to your managers and the leadership. It only makes sense to rant anonymously on a public platform if all these steps have failed, and yet things didn't improve. Why do I get a strong feeling that most of you haven't done that?

